        <li class="flex gap-4">
          <span class="font-bold text-primary text-lg">1</span>
          <div>
            <h4 class="font-bold text-on-surface mb-2">Cutting Tools</h4>
            <p class="font-body text-on-surface text-sm">Use a sharp craft knife, utility blade, or hot-wire cutter. A T-square helps ensure straight cuts. For curves, a rotary cutter works well.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="flex gap-4">
          <span class="font-bold text-primary text-lg">2</span>
          <div>
            <h4 class="font-bold text-on-surface mb-2">Adhesives & Assembly</h4>
            <p class="font-body text-on-surface text-sm">White glue (PVA), hot glue, and packaging tape work well. For permanent bonds, contact cement is excellent. Avoid water-based glues on unfinished cardboard (they cause warping).</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="flex gap-4">
          <span class="font-bold text-primary text-lg">3</span>
          <div>
            <h4 class="font-bold text-on-surface mb-2">Painting & Finishing</h4>
            <p class="font-body text-on-surface text-sm">Acrylic paint, marker, and spray paint all work. For water-resistant finishes, seal with clear polyurethane or varnish. Test on scrap pieces first.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="flex gap-4">
          <span class="font-bold text-primary text-lg">4</span>
          <div>
            <h4 class="font-bold text-on-surface mb-2">Storage & Transport</h4>
            <p class="font-body text-on-surface text-sm">Store sheets flat in a dry environment. Humidity and moisture can warp corrugated cardboard. Transport carefully to avoid creasing.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>
